01:02:09.650 --> 01:02:12.483
First, here is White House
correspondent Sam Donaldson.

01:02:14.070 --> 01:02:15.730
- [Sam] Four hours after the strike began,

01:02:15.730 --> 01:02:18.470
President Reagan described
the aides as very angry

01:02:18.470 --> 01:02:19.430
and very determined

01:02:19.430 --> 01:02:21.640
to serve notice on the
air traffic controllers

01:02:21.640 --> 01:02:24.870
that they had better return
to work quickly or else.

01:02:24.870 --> 01:02:27.580
- Government cannot close
down the assembly line.

01:02:27.580 --> 01:02:30.050
It has to provide without interruption

01:02:30.050 --> 01:02:31.300
the protective services

01:02:31.300 --> 01:02:33.497
which are government's reason for being.

01:02:33.497 --> 01:02:35.223
It was in recognition of this

01:02:35.223 --> 01:02:37.533
that the Congress passed a law

01:02:37.533 --> 01:02:40.062
forbidding strikes by government employees

01:02:40.062 --> 01:02:42.107
against the public safety.

01:02:42.107 --> 01:02:45.137
It is for this reason
that I must tell those

01:02:45.137 --> 01:02:48.710
who fail to report for duty this morning,

01:02:48.710 --> 01:02:50.852
they are in violation of the law

01:02:50.852 --> 01:02:54.800
and if they do not report
for work within 48 hours,

01:02:54.800 --> 01:02:58.500
they have forfeited their
jobs and will be terminated.

01:02:58.500 --> 01:03:00.350
- [Sam] Strong as the
threat of firing may be,

01:03:00.350 --> 01:03:01.420
the administration moved rapidly

01:03:01.420 --> 01:03:03.370
to employ other weapons as well.

01:03:03.370 --> 01:03:05.780
Court proceedings to force
the strikers back to work

01:03:05.780 --> 01:03:08.010
were begun in 19 separate courts.

01:03:08.010 --> 01:03:10.780
Criminal charges were being
prepared against individuals.

01:03:10.780 --> 01:03:13.230
The first cases would be
brought against union leaders,

01:03:13.230 --> 01:03:16.620
but FBI agents are compiling
a complete list of strikers.

01:03:16.620 --> 01:03:19.030
The union's three and a half
million dollar strike fund

01:03:19.030 --> 01:03:20.602
has been impounded by court order

01:03:20.602 --> 01:03:22.084
and a petition has been filed

01:03:22.084 --> 01:03:24.254
asking for decertification of the union

01:03:24.254 --> 01:03:27.170
meaning to put it out
of business permanently.

01:03:27.170 --> 01:03:30.230
The President was asked why
such strong action immediately?

01:03:30.230 --> 01:03:32.550
Why not some lesser action to begin with?

01:03:32.550 --> 01:03:34.860
- What lesser action can there be?

01:03:34.860 --> 01:03:37.356
The law is very explicit.

01:03:37.356 --> 01:03:39.670
They are violating the law.

01:03:39.670 --> 01:03:41.669
- The President is said by
an aide to be tough as nails

01:03:41.669 --> 01:03:44.000
in his determination to break this strike.

01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:46.160
And this morning, Mr. Reagan
reminisced in the Oval Office

01:03:46.160 --> 01:03:48.262
about Calvin Coolidge's
similar determination

01:03:48.262 --> 01:03:52.043
and success in breaking the
Boston Police strike of 1919

01:03:52.043 --> 01:03:54.960
when Coolidge was
governor of Massachusetts.

01:03:54.960 --> 01:03:56.780
In this case, Mr. Reagan wanted to make

01:03:56.780 --> 01:03:59.240
the deadline for firing 24 hours at first.

01:03:59.240 --> 01:04:00.861
He finally settled on 48

01:04:00.861 --> 01:04:02.140
in order to make certain

01:04:02.140 --> 01:04:04.160
that no air traffic
controller could say later,

01:04:04.160 --> 01:04:05.780
he didn't get the word.

01:04:05.780 --> 01:04:08.200
The President seems convinced
that by being tough,

01:04:08.200 --> 01:04:11.010
he can force many of the
union members back to work.

01:04:11.010 --> 01:04:12.160
He also seems convinced

01:04:12.160 --> 01:04:15.020
that being tough is what the public wants.

01:04:15.020 --> 01:04:17.617
Sam Donaldson, ABC News, the White House.

01:04:17.617 --> 01:04:21.150
- And he did indeed fire
those air traffic controllers.

01:04:21.150 --> 01:04:24.372
Let's go forward three years in the UK.

01:04:24.372 --> 01:04:27.110
- Mr. Chairman, what we have
seen in the past few weeks

01:04:27.110 --> 01:04:29.393
is not picketing at all.

01:04:30.282 --> 01:04:33.730
It is an attempt by
force to prevent others

01:04:33.730 --> 01:04:36.851
from doing what they have a right to do.

01:04:36.851 --> 01:04:40.018
(audience applauding)

01:04:43.856 --> 01:04:45.439
It is intimidation.

01:04:46.510 --> 01:04:48.722
It is unlawful assembly.

01:04:48.722 --> 01:04:53.722
Our duty demands and the
national interest requires

01:04:53.760 --> 01:04:56.930
that we see that violence does not pay

01:04:56.930 --> 01:04:59.115
and is seen not to pay.

01:04:59.115 --> 01:05:02.282
(audience applauding)

01:05:04.640 --> 01:05:07.410
Let violence cease.

01:05:07.410 --> 01:05:09.496
Let the law be kept.

01:05:09.496 --> 01:05:13.137
That is the spoken and unspoken hope

01:05:13.137 --> 01:05:17.363
and wish of millions
of our fellow citizens.

01:05:18.955 --> 01:05:22.949
- So those two confrontations
were emblematic

01:05:22.949 --> 01:05:26.730
of the gloves coming off with
the rise of the new right

01:05:26.730 --> 01:05:31.730
when Ronald Reagan fired the
air traffic controllers in 1981

01:05:32.007 --> 01:05:34.730
and Margaret Thatcher took on the miners

01:05:34.730 --> 01:05:39.080
who had been striking through
much of the 1970s in Britain

01:05:40.130 --> 01:05:43.683
and broke the miner's union.

01:05:43.683 --> 01:05:47.796
And this signaled a start
of a very different attitude

01:05:47.796 --> 01:05:52.796
toward unions on the part
of right of center parties.

01:05:53.230 --> 01:05:58.060
And many people sort of
date the big change here

01:05:58.060 --> 01:05:59.951
to those governments

01:05:59.951 --> 01:06:04.810
and those particular sort
of symbolic confrontations.

01:06:04.810 --> 01:06:09.570
But the truth is that that
was the tip of an iceberg

01:06:09.570 --> 01:06:12.410
that has a much longer provenance.

01:06:12.410 --> 01:06:15.129
So if you look at union
membership in the US,

01:06:15.129 --> 01:06:20.129
you can see this starts
from, goes from 1973 to 2009,

01:06:21.294 --> 01:06:23.833
and it basically falls in half.

01:06:23.833 --> 01:06:28.682
And if you take out public sector workers,

01:06:28.682 --> 01:06:33.682
it's overall union membership
falls even more dramatically.

01:06:36.370 --> 01:06:37.610
You can see here

01:06:39.270 --> 01:06:44.270
that private sector unions
have all but disappeared.

01:06:45.620 --> 01:06:48.010
But what do these numbers ignore?

01:06:48.010 --> 01:06:51.053
What do these graphs not tell us?

01:06:52.580 --> 01:06:53.750
Most people know that.

01:06:53.750 --> 01:06:56.620
Most people know that since the 1970s,

01:06:56.620 --> 01:06:57.785
unionist rates,

01:06:57.785 --> 01:07:00.500
unions have gotten a lot smaller.

01:07:00.500 --> 01:07:01.333
Yeah?

01:07:01.333 --> 01:07:03.095
- [Male Speaker] There are
a lot of jobs going away.

01:07:03.095 --> 01:07:04.490
- Yup, that's true,

01:07:04.490 --> 01:07:05.323
but what else,

01:07:05.323 --> 01:07:07.363
what do these numbers not tell us?

01:07:08.684 --> 01:07:13.360
What they don't tell us is
it's not since the 1970s.

01:07:13.360 --> 01:07:15.212
It's since the 1950s

01:07:15.212 --> 01:07:18.831
that the high watermark
of union membership

01:07:18.831 --> 01:07:22.108
in the US economy

01:07:22.108 --> 01:07:27.108
is really in the late
1940s and early 1950s.

01:07:30.100 --> 01:07:32.500
The Wagner Act protecting unions

01:07:32.500 --> 01:07:35.010
had been passed in 1935

01:07:35.010 --> 01:07:38.190
as part of FDR's new deal legislation

01:07:38.190 --> 01:07:43.190
and had had very tepid opposition
from business initially

01:07:44.224 --> 01:07:48.250
partly because of the fears of Communism,

01:07:48.250 --> 01:07:49.854
but that rapidly changed

01:07:49.854 --> 01:07:52.810
once it became obvious that the US economy

01:07:52.810 --> 01:07:56.954
was not gonna disappear,
was not gonna collapse.

01:07:56.954 --> 01:07:59.325
And through much of the 1940s,

01:07:59.325 --> 01:08:01.460
there was a lot of lobbying

01:08:01.460 --> 01:08:04.480
to either get rid of
Wagner or cut it back.

01:08:04.480 --> 01:08:09.480
And in 1947, Republican Congress
passed the Taft-Hartley Act

01:08:10.713 --> 01:08:15.630
which over President
Truman's veto by the way,

01:08:15.630 --> 01:08:19.110
so it was a very powerful
Republican Congress did that,

01:08:19.110 --> 01:08:21.440
takes 2/3 in both houses,

01:08:21.440 --> 01:08:25.640
and Taft-Hartley cut back on
a lot of union protections.

01:08:25.640 --> 01:08:27.346
So part of it was the politics,

01:08:27.346 --> 01:08:31.466
but we've seen as America has transformed

01:08:31.466 --> 01:08:36.000
from a manufacturing
to a services economy,

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:38.690
it's become less and less unionized

01:08:38.690 --> 01:08:40.850
partly for those sorts
of political reasons

01:08:40.850 --> 01:08:42.470
and part because it's much harder

01:08:42.470 --> 01:08:46.325
to organize service sector
than it is manufacturing,

01:08:46.325 --> 01:08:48.684
and mining, and things like that,

01:08:48.684 --> 01:08:51.460
and partly because more recently,

01:08:51.460 --> 01:08:54.800
the advent of free trade.

01:08:54.800 --> 01:08:58.987
The fact that capital is
back to the Hirschman point,

01:09:01.525 --> 01:09:05.380
capital has many fewer
exit costs than labor.

01:09:05.380 --> 01:09:07.820
Capital is more mobile than labor,

01:09:07.820 --> 01:09:12.640
so capital can leave at
much lower cost than labor.

01:09:12.640 --> 01:09:15.513
Think about what I said
about different exit costs

01:09:15.513 --> 01:09:18.610
being important when we
talked about Hirschman.

01:09:18.610 --> 01:09:20.260
And those exit costs for capital

01:09:20.260 --> 01:09:22.290
have come down, and down, and down,

01:09:22.290 --> 01:09:25.494
and so we saw last time

01:09:25.494 --> 01:09:27.620
if they can't make enough money in China,

01:09:27.620 --> 01:09:29.390
they just move to Vietnam.

01:09:29.390 --> 01:09:32.900
And then they'll go to
Cambodia or some place else.

01:09:32.900 --> 01:09:35.430
So you've got low exit cost for capital,

01:09:35.430 --> 01:09:37.251
higher exit cost for labor.

01:09:37.251 --> 01:09:42.251
And so that makes it very
difficult to sustain unionization.

01:09:42.387 --> 01:09:47.051
And this as somebody said
when we were talking about,

01:09:47.051 --> 01:09:49.793
this has a lot to do,

01:09:51.110 --> 01:09:53.204
the red line there is
a share of the income

01:09:53.204 --> 01:09:55.027
going to the top 10%

01:09:55.027 --> 01:09:58.125
and the blue line is the
decline in unionization

01:09:58.125 --> 01:09:59.507
since the '50s.

01:09:59.507 --> 01:10:00.730
And as you can see,

01:10:00.730 --> 01:10:04.057
as unions get smaller and smaller,

01:10:04.057 --> 01:10:07.043
the inequality is growing.

01:10:07.976 --> 01:10:11.380
And somebody else mentioned
as this has happened,

01:10:11.380 --> 01:10:13.770
we've seen a declining share of income

01:10:13.770 --> 01:10:15.350
going to the middle class.

01:10:15.350 --> 01:10:17.050
Again, I'll post these slides

01:10:17.050 --> 01:10:20.891
and you can look at them at your leisure.

01:10:20.891 --> 01:10:24.663
And this is not only the case in the US.

01:10:26.926 --> 01:10:29.850
You won't be able to see these probably,

01:10:29.850 --> 01:10:33.520
but these are all countries
in which a different.

01:10:33.520 --> 01:10:35.658
You'll be able to see
them when I post them.

01:10:35.658 --> 01:10:37.120
They're all countries

01:10:37.120 --> 01:10:41.690
in which the proportion of the work force

01:10:42.540 --> 01:10:47.030
has declined over the
last several decades.

01:10:47.030 --> 01:10:49.310
And they're all the major economies.

01:10:49.310 --> 01:10:51.730
Unions have become smaller and weaker.

01:10:51.730 --> 01:10:53.360
There are a few exceptions,

01:10:53.360 --> 01:10:55.886
places like Belgium, Chile, Mexico.

01:10:55.886 --> 01:10:58.592
It's more or less remained flat.

01:10:58.592 --> 01:11:02.160
It seems like Finland is about
the only country in the world

01:11:02.160 --> 01:11:06.304
in which unionization rates
have actually increased.

01:11:06.304 --> 01:11:08.519
And so what are the implications of that?

01:11:08.519 --> 01:11:12.730
The implications of that are that unions

01:11:12.730 --> 01:11:14.651
which as the gentleman here said

01:11:14.651 --> 01:11:17.712
are probably the best
institutional component

01:11:17.712 --> 01:11:22.480
for creating solidarity among voters

01:11:22.480 --> 01:11:24.250
to vote for certain platforms

01:11:24.250 --> 01:11:27.923
are decreasingly well equipped to do that.

01:11:27.923 --> 01:11:31.330
And particularly, it has
been conventional wisdom

01:11:31.330 --> 01:11:33.092
that in two-party systems,

01:11:33.092 --> 01:11:36.775
the unionized workforce
is relatively small

01:11:36.775 --> 01:11:41.775
so it's not gonna be able to
get a lot of redistribution.

01:11:43.369 --> 01:11:48.157
And so this is a picture
of inequalities in the US,

01:11:50.240 --> 01:11:54.293
the UK, Germany, and France
over the past century.

01:11:54.293 --> 01:11:56.760
For all countries, it's this U shape.

01:11:56.760 --> 01:11:59.776
So we go from the gilded
age to where we are now

01:11:59.776 --> 01:12:02.560
more or less in this U shape

01:12:02.560 --> 01:12:07.560
with the more equality in
the middle of the century.

01:12:08.450 --> 01:12:09.625
But as you can see,

01:12:09.625 --> 01:12:12.763
the U is deeper in the US and the UK

01:12:12.763 --> 01:12:14.730
which have two party systems

01:12:14.730 --> 01:12:17.088
and it's shallower in France and Germany

01:12:17.088 --> 01:12:19.717
which have multiparty systems.

01:12:19.717 --> 01:12:24.702
And this has been a source
of the conventional wisdom

01:12:24.702 --> 01:12:26.700
that two-party systems

01:12:26.700 --> 01:12:29.814
are less redistributive
to the median voter

01:12:29.814 --> 01:12:31.760
than multi-party systems.

01:12:31.760 --> 01:12:36.380
This has been conventional
wisdom for a very long time.

01:12:36.380 --> 01:12:41.380
And part of the reason here
is as the left of center party

01:12:42.562 --> 01:12:46.718
is less and less connected
to a powerful union movement,

01:12:46.718 --> 01:12:49.600
there's gonna be less demand on it

01:12:49.600 --> 01:12:53.560
to deliver those kinds of
redistributive changes.

01:12:53.560 --> 01:12:55.680
And indeed, there's scholarship

01:12:55.680 --> 01:12:57.730
mostly from 20 or 30 years ago

01:12:57.730 --> 01:13:00.470
suggesting that multi-party systems

01:13:00.470 --> 01:13:03.470
are more responsive to the median voter

01:13:03.470 --> 01:13:06.323
in the policies that they actually enact.

01:13:07.192 --> 01:13:10.200
Whether that is in fact true anymore

01:13:10.200 --> 01:13:12.367
is what we'll talk about next time.

01:13:12.367 --> 01:13:13.723
See you on Tuesday.

01:13:16.972 --> 01:13:19.389
(calm music)

